### [Psalms Chapter 120](../../../bib/kjv/psa120.htm#001.md)

[Psalms 120:2](../../../bib/kjv/psa120.htm#002.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_002">psa 120:2</span></span>

This is the first of fifteen Psalms (Psalms 120-134) entitled "A Song of
Degrees" ([Psa 121:1](../../../bib/kjv/psa121.htm#001.md) --literally, "A
song for the degrees"), or ascents. It seems most probable they were
designed for the use of the people when going up (compare [Kg1
12:27-28](../../../bib/kjv/kg1012.htm#027).md) to Jerusalem on the festival
occasions ([Deu 16:16](../../../bib/kjv/deu016.htm#016).md), three times a
year. David appears as the author of four, Solomon of one ([Psa
127:1](../../../bib/kjv/psa127.htm#001).md), and the other ten are
anonymous, probably composed after the captivity. In this Psalm the
writer acknowledges God's mercy, prays for relief from a malicious foe,
whose punishment he anticipates, and then repeats his complaint. ([Psa
120:1-7](../../../bib/kjv/psa120.htm#001).md)

Slander and deceit charged on his foes implies his innocence.

