52:4](../../../bib/kjv/psa052.htm#004.md).

[Psalms 120:4](../../../bib/kjv/psa120.htm#004.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_004">psa 120:4</span></span>

Sharp arrows of the mighty--destructive inflictions.

coals of juniper--which retain heat long. This verse may be read as a
description of the wicked, but better as their punishment, in reply to
the question of [Psa 120:3](../../../bib/kjv/psa120.htm#003.md).

[Psalms 120:5](../../../bib/kjv/psa120.htm#005.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_005">psa 120:5</span></span>

A residence in these remote lands pictures his miserable condition.

[Psalms 120:6](../../../bib/kjv/psa120.htm#006.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_006">psa 120:6</span></span>

While those who surrounded him were maliciously hostile, he was disposed
to peace. This Psalm may well begin such a series as this, as a contrast
to the promised joys of God's worship.

